-- stdlib/passes/validate.ev — self-hosted external-only check.
--
-- The Evident-side twin of runtime/src/runtime/validate.rs's
-- `enforce_external_only`: the load-time rule that rejects
-- non-`external` schemas which directly construct FFI effects
-- (`FFICall` / `FFIOpen` / `FFILookup` / `LibCall`). Demos and
-- ordinary library code reach C through `external claim` wrappers
-- in `packages/` and `stdlib/posix.ev`; the runtime refuses to
-- compile a non-`external` claim that does so itself.
--
-- This pass owns the decision logic — what counts as a banned
-- call name. The Rust shim in runtime/src/portable/validate.rs
-- owns the walk: it iterates a schema's body items, recurses into
-- each Constraint's Expr tree, and queries `ValidateExpr` with the
-- call name at every Call node. Per-Call classification lives in
-- Evident; structural recursion stays in Rust because the language
-- can't recurse over nested Expr trees yet (see
-- `docs/self-hosting.md`). The shim's walk mirrors `find_ffi_call`
-- in `runtime/src/runtime/validate.rs` exactly, so both impls emit
-- byte-identical diagnostics.
--
-- ── Why `nm ∈ String` and not `e ∈ Expr` ──────────────────────
-- The natural shape — match the whole Expr, destructure ECall, pin
-- and compare its name field — runs into a runtime gap: a String
-- payload extracted from a given-pinned enum value doesn't preserve
-- byte equality with a source-literal string. `match e { ECall(nm,
-- _) ⇒ (nm = "FFICall" ? ...) }` evaluates the comparison to false
-- on both JIT and slow paths even when the bytes match. Pinning
-- `nm` directly side-steps the gap: the runtime threads the
-- given-bound String to the comparison without going through the
-- enum-extractor. The pattern is still genuinely self-hosted (the
-- "banned ⇔ name ∈ {...}" decision lives here), and the shim's
-- Rust walker decides WHEN to ask. See
-- `examples/COUNTEREXAMPLES.md` for the gap entry.
--
-- ── Faithful subset ───────────────────────────────────────────
-- Byte-identical to `enforce_external_only` for every input shape.
-- The Rust shim drives the recursion, so every expression tree the
-- canonical walker visits, this pass classifies. The pass is total
-- (banned names map to themselves, everything else to "").

import "stdlib/ast.ev"

-- Classify a call name. Returns `nm` itself when it's one of the
-- four banned FFI-construction primitives; empty string otherwise.
-- The shim treats a non-empty return as a found-violation signal
-- and uses the returned name in the diagnostic.
claim ValidateExpr
    nm ∈ String
    out ∈ String
    out = ((nm = "FFICall" ∨ nm = "FFIOpen" ∨ nm = "FFILookup" ∨ nm = "LibCall") ? nm : "")
